                    "company": "Wageningen University & Research",
                    "description": "In this research I conducted a detailed farm characterization in the eastern and south western highlands of Uganda. Based on a rapid farm characterization survey (125 households), a farm typology of in total five farm types (four in each location) was constructed. For each farm type four households were randomly selected (32 in total) for a detailed farm characterization (socio-economic information, measured field sizes and yields). Opportunities and constrains for climbing bean cultivation were explored for the different farm types. The main findings were that climbing bean cultivation and yields did only partly differ for different farm types. Poor soil fertility and pests(rats) were the main cause for poor yields in the south-western highlands. Intercropping climbing bean in coffee-banana systems and a lack of knowledge on climbing bean cultivation resulted in low yields in the eastern highlands. Currently this knowledge is used to develop and target options for improved climbing bean cultivation in both areas within the N2Africa project.",
                    "title": "MSc thesis research N2Africa",
                    "employment_type": null
                },
